songs.comment:
I oscillated wildly on what to submit for this. Ultimately i've landed on actual deep emotional connection, which is probably a bad idea as historically thats meant downvotes... 

In my early 20s i suffered a debilitating burnout. I didn't realise, but i lost my love of music for about 9 months. It had no joy for me. Until one evening I was playing no man's sky (a melancholic love letter to my childhood sci-fi favourites) and as you leave the atmosphere of the first planet you start on, this song plays. It made me absolutely weep. I felt an emotional reaction to music! I suddenly realised how much that had been absent. Since this round clearly favours the musically knowledgable I was planning to sneak in at midnight and grab up that prime MTV Unplugged real estate.

Many of the songs I considered were soft and mellifluous. Gentle like a summer rain, light and bubbling like a mountain spring.

This song is the wave that pulls you under, grates you across the seabed, then dashes you against the rocks.

It has one of my favourite lines ever. Obscene and visceral, I wish I could spit it at every man who's ever harassed, patronised, or belittled me: 
"I don't only bite but I'm rabid
Try to pet my fucking head again 
And I'mma put a tooth through the flesh 
Of the palm that you jack with."

El-P grapples with his nihilistic, self-destructive behaviours. Meanwhile, Killer Mike takes aim at the false idols of hip hop and *eviscerates* Jay-Z and Kanye.

What's it got to do with the sea though? I'm so glad you asked, Charlie. I have no fucking clue. I think it's about the woozy, seasick feeling of cognitive dissonance. Living in a world so fucked that it makes you feel like you're losing your mind. Welcome to America: home of the anger, home of the evil.

I did struggle to think of any music that can be inappropriate at a funeral. Anything goes. And that’s kind of great.

Requiem = very appropriate music for a funeral.

Calling the dead a ‘twat’ or a ‘prick’ = probably (hopefully) inappropriate music for a funeral.

Nirvana were trying to record Lithium in the studio and it just wasn't working, and they were all seriously frustrated. quotes.text: This song has a special place for me. I had left the coast of South Kent to head to Birmingham where I thought I would be free, but with that freedom I completely lost control. 2 months into year 2 I walked away from uni and from Brum and returned to Kent. I was broken. I got two jobs, one in Burger King and the other in a supermarket in Hythe stacking shelves. Every lunch break me and this dude walked up to the beach to burn one and  listen to tunes. It was a pretty shit time in my life, he said have you heard this album by Morcheeba, he played it. I was blown away, I felt soothed and this track just spoke to me, I had left my soul by the sea. It made those next 3 months of my life more bearable and kickstarted a change in direction which saw me head out to work at a camp in America where I truly discovered myself...anyways not sure why all that is relevant but having considered this track I decided it was bit boring all these years later but have a vote for the fond memory invoked.
quotes.author: Bino

quotes.text:
Many of the songs I considered were soft and mellifluous. Gentle like a summer rain, light and bubbling like a mountain spring.

This song is the wave that pulls you under, grates you across the seabed, then dashes you against the rocks.

It has one of my favourite lines ever. Obscene and visceral, I wish I could spit it at every man who's ever harassed, patronised, or belittled me: 
"I don't only bite but I'm rabid
Try to pet my fucking head again 
And I'mma put a tooth through the flesh 
Of the palm that you jack with."

El-P grapples with his nihilistic, self-destructive behaviours. Meanwhile, Killer Mike takes aim at the false idols of hip hop and *eviscerates* Jay-Z and Kanye.

What's it got to do with the sea though? I'm so glad you asked, Charlie. I have no fucking clue. I think it's about the woozy, seasick feeling of cognitive dissonance. Living in a world so fucked that it makes you feel like you're losing your mind. Welcome to America: home of the anger, home of the evil.

quotes.text:
"Oh, is Nevermind the one with Teen Spirit?" No mate it's the one with this on it. 
I listened to Nevermind a *lot* when I was a kid. I used to fall asleep with it on my headphones. Something In The Way would end and I'd drift off. Then ten minutes of silence, and suddenly this slab of mindless violence would start up and I would wake up terrified. One of the classic 90s Hidden Tracks. Happened dozens of times. Happy memories.
Nirvana were trying to record Lithium in the studio and it just wasn't working, and they were all seriously frustrated. Cobain told their producer (and Garbage founder) Butch Vig to keep rolling, and they recorded this live in one take. Kurt promptly smashed his guitar to matchsticks and stormed out.
Vig said, well, guess that's it for today, sent everyone home, and went out to try and find a new left-handed Stratocaster before the next day's session...

Just as it reaches 1:38 and that monstrous bass loosens every bowel in the house, I step out in red speedos and Where's Wally thick-rimmed specs. The crowd boos and hurls rotten veg. 
"THE STRAW-WEIGHT CHAMPION OF THE WORRRRRRRRRRRRRLD...BENEDICT, 'NO SEX FOR BEN', JOOOOOOOOOOOOOOONES."
My crowd walk starts at 3:00 as the bass drum thud properly starts up. By the time I am stepping into the ring to meet my doom, it reaches 3:55 and the wonky clanky beat settles into that amazing square groove. 
I am kocked out in round 2, sustaining a severe and debilitating brain injury, but hum this tune all the way to the hospital. 
Fin.
quotes.author: Ben

quotes.text:
Since this round clearly favours the musically knowledgable I was planning to sneak in at midnight and grab up that prime MTV Unplugged real estate. 

But then I thought, nah. What could be better than a great track from a live album that I’m actually in. Yup that’s me 🙋in the background, soaked in other folks’ sweat and Guinness, cheering along with ten thousand people at the Dublin o2. 

It’s not the Horslips’ best tune, but it’s the best tune on a live album recorded, let’s be honest, when the band were well past their best - by this point the bassist had Parkinson’s, and the drummer was so arthritic it’s actually his 40 year old son on stage. But no one else would become their cover band so they had to do it themselves. Irish folk prog rock at its best. Enjoy.
quotes.author: Surrealist

quotes.text:
The Good, The Bad, and The Queen is Damon Albarn, Paul Simonon (the Clash's bassist - that's him on the cover of London Calling), Tony Allen (Fela Kuti's drummer and legendary Afrobeat pioneer), and Simon Tong (the Verve's guitarist). The second album, from whence cometh this dubby, sludgy slice of weird, is called The Merrie Land, an incredible bit of work about England in the 21st Century. 
They toured the album briefly in 2019, and when Allen died a year later aged 79, Albarn announced there would be no more TGTBaTQ music. 
What a groove this tune has - the bassline is perfection, but the guitar in the background throughout just sets it off. And those horns! Continually tripping over its own shoelaces, and yet somehow unstoppable. Chicken collector man - hey!
quotes.author: Ben

quotes.text: It’s Friday night at Glastonbury festival and the year is 1999. The year of fear for the coming millennium bug, we’re told that we absolutely must shit ourselves, this bug is going to destroy us all! Preppers are making final tweaks to their setups, the obscenely rich are picking out islands to retreat to and the geeks are coding fixes into computer systems to ensure we don’t have a system error to end all system errors. REM decided to send a message with their final song of the night along with a 100,000 friends and how beautiful that was. Wish I was there for it! Stipe (lead singer) also loses the mic in the crowd which has quite funny consequences until the engineer switches it off! So many tunes from this set but none quite so poignant.
quotes.author: Ghandi El-Chamaa
quotes.context: submitting 'It's The End Of The World As We Know It (And I Feel Fine) - Live From Pyramid Stage, Glastonbury Festival / 1999'
quotes.song_title: It's The End Of The World As We Know It (And I Feel Fine) - Live From Pyramid Stage, Glastonbury Festival / 1999

quotes.text:
I oscillated wildly on what to submit for this. Ultimately i've landed on actual deep emotional connection, which is probably a bad idea as historically thats meant downvotes... 

In my early 20s i suffered a debilitating burnout. I didn't realise, but i lost my love of music for about 9 months. It had no joy for me. Until one evening I was playing no man's sky (a melancholic love letter to my childhood sci-fi favourites) and as you leave the atmosphere of the first planet you start on, this song plays. It made me absolutely weep. I felt an emotional reaction to music! I suddenly realised how much that had been absent. This song is forever burned into me - the one that marks the dividing line between bad and good. <3
quotes.author: basssbear

quotes.text:
I've tried a lot of different combinations: wildly unlikely collab but ridiculous song, great song but the collab is unsurprising. Great song but I don't know the artists well enough to know if it's unlikely... There was even a Nas/Damien Marley/Lil Wayne/Joss Stone collab that it turns out the world didn't need.

This is, to my mind, a cracking tune with a truly unusual combination of talent. Gospel singer and civil rights activist Mavis Staples (of the Staple Singers, I'll Take You There) provides a hauntingly bitter refrain over QOTSA's Josh Homme's guitar riffs and moody background vocals, while El-P and Killer Mike rail against a systemically corrupt political elite.

quotes.song_title: pulling the pin (feat. Mavis Staples & Josh Homme)

quotes.text: So the issue I have with live albums is it's just a total compromise on quality. I want to listen to the music. I love live music, but that's an experience that doesn't imo translate to a recording. I'd much rather listen to something actually engineered for the medium. Anyway so I went through a few live artists I do like but all the live recordings just sacrificed too much. Except this one. Absolute props to the sound engineers, it's easily the clearest lushest live recording I've listened to this morning. And I listened to at least 3, so I'm confident it's an outlier. Also I fucking love this song and it was my ADHD repeat tune for about 4 months. Banger.
quotes.author: basssbear

quotes.text: My light spacecraft, Weaver, is being fuelled and loaded in a bustling and dirty spaceport on Mars. A klaxon sounds and symbols flash up on the screens in front of me in the cockpit; we’re good to go. I flick and adjust various flashing buttons and dials in front of my before pulling back the thruster leaver, lift off! The acceleration presses me back into my seat as we jet into the red crimson sky. We approach the giant star gate orbiting in space above Mars and are slingshotted through into warp speed. The pin points of lights twinkling around me streak into trails and fuse into one bright mass as we are thrown out into deep space.
quotes.author: Shimonster
quotes.round_name: The Dark Side of the Tune

quotes.text:
This one makes me cry every time I listen to it. On a basic level, it's about the eruption of Vesuvius and the people caught in it (the chorus is eheu which is the Latin for 'alas'). Then I hear the words "does it almost feel like you've been here before?" And I think about all the disasters that have befallen me in my life. All the miscarriages, the arguments, the violence, the trauma, the people I have lost (I have lost a lot of people). And the refrain "how am I gonna be an optimist about this?" - it's something I've had to ask myself far too many times in my life.

WAY TO MAKE A NATURAL DISASTER ALL ABOUT MYSELF AMIRITE
quotes.author: Kate Hitchcock

quotes.text: Started on Rotator - Come Get Some, which is a right old racket.  Landed on this, and a lot of things that weren't anywhere near as hard as the starting track, so this'll do, Peg.  Both excellent live, once I bought a stick of rock with a smiley face in along to a Bong-Ra gig and gave it to someone else who, while mashed, I thought looked like him.  Later asked him how it was.  He had no clue.  Then I found the original guy again and accused him of pretences.  Don't go raving by yourself, kids.  Strong recommend for both these 2 live though, and anyone who likes Igorrr should check out Full Metal Racket.

quotes.text: I understand it might be very unBritish of me to say, but when it comes to Pulp, I really don’t understand what the whole fuss is about 😉. I mean, I get how big they are / have been, and how they definitely represent a very typical British 90’s sound. But I’ve never been wowed so much by them. Jarvis Cocker is an absolute legend and one of the great Frenchised Brit ever! I guess I’m in such awe of the crazy shit amount of good sounds that have been coming from this tiny island, generally over a century and then specifically in that decade… anyway, I thought this song was ok though in the end.

quotes.context: on 'Do You Remember The First Time?'
quotes.song_title: Do You Remember The First Time?

quotes.text: I Was that one dick head at school that always carried a camera around. Every cider drunk night on the park or youth club and I’m the only one with photographic evidence of the 90’s. I’m sentimental and I’m a documenter. I’ve written in a journal every day of my life and have boxes full of photos and memories. People ask to come round and look through my boxes or ask to take away photos for weddings or funerals. So even though I’ve always loved this song, the older I get the more emotional it is ‘the red box of memories’ . I heard it live for the first time last year, and yes I cried
quotes.author: annamariawh

quotes.text:
I did struggle to think of any music that can be inappropriate at a funeral. Anything goes. And that’s kind of great.

Still. Thinking to fit the script whilst sticking to cherished music, I selected this film soundtrack I have always loved, by an immense artist, Serge Gainsbourg. It translates as ‘Requiem for a twat’, or ‘Requiem for a prick’.

Requiem = very appropriate music for a funeral.

Calling the dead a ‘twat’ or a ‘prick’ = probably (hopefully) inappropriate music for a funeral.

It is fun, cynical, sharp and witty, in both the sounds and words. An absolute timeless tune.
quotes.author: Juju

quotes.text:
Introduced to Djet-X at a random house party by a former BBC sound recordist who spent his career travelling the globe, mostly doing nature docs or covering war zones, and taking the opportunity to trawl local record shops during his downtime. Djet-X are from his time spent in the latter category - a Haitian funk band with a unique sound.

Not speaking French, let alone creole, I have no idea what they’re singing about here, but I’m happy with that, just letting their voices wash over me as another layer of sound.

Enjoy something a little different from the Caribbean.
quotes.author: Surrealist

quotes.text:
I loved this back in the day and it holds up. Excellent chords. I always thought of this as being about a love affair but looking at the lyrics and doing a bit of Googling, it's a lament for the optimism of the Apollo programme and the big fat nothing that followed.  Definitely still resonant, couldn't nail the brief harder. Stunner, highlight of the round.
Did we fly to the moon too soon? Did we squander the chance?
In the rush of the race, the reason we chase is lost in romance
And still we try to justify the waste
For a taste of man's greatest adventure
quotes.author: Ben
quotes.round_name: The Dark Side of the Tune

quotes.text:
I love this song and how these guys randomly came together.

"Merry Clayton was called into the studio late at night in 1969—pregnant, in her pajamas, and still wearing hair rollers—to record the backing vocal for “Gimme Shelter.” The Stones needed a powerful voice at the last minute, and she delivered one of the most iconic vocal takes in rock history. Her raw, cracking, unbelievable performance didn’t just elevate the song; it transformed it."

Short video of them talking about it:
https://www.facebook.com/share/v/1Bt7u6bReM/

quotes.text:

"We don't think that would end well."
"Right so, will we just make a dub track then?"
"OK safe, you're on."

How many bands have had to re-evaluate their careers, their life choices even, when they found themselves after Portishead on a lineup? When the playlist loaded, I had that same sinking feeling.

But I stand by my choice. I think Talking Heads are a phenomenal live band and this song has such energy; the afrobeat percussion, Tina Weymouth's funk-influenced bass. The lyrics are from a Dadaist nonsense poem by Hugo Ball, I nearly submitted it for the last round. 

I hope at least one of you liked it a lot.

quotes.text: You’re Swaggering down toward the ring telling members of the crowd to fuck off for no reason. You enter the ring chewing gum, your opponent looks on murderous, one of the people you told to fuck off was his mum. The bell sounds and he KOs you in the first round with an uppercut that held all the memories of how his mother held him tight at night after a particularly heavy nightmare - it sends you skyward causing you to call out for your own mummy.

quotes.text:
I hit the jackpot! First go on the spotify radio one armed bandit and I get one of my fav shpongle songs. I went to my workzoneout playlist and did radio on the first song, which was "How the jellyfish jumped up the mountain" by shpongle which is another cracker of a tune.

quotes.text: I'm not sure I like this, but I have to award it a point because it understood the assignment. When Narrator starts talking about his dry mouth, watering eyes, and ringing ears, I felt the creeping unease of sci-fi body horror. As the song built, I felt more and more anxiety, imagining the alien illness overtaking our Narrator and warping his DNA. Congratulations, I'm horri-sci-fied and do not want to visit Planet Shpongle.
quotes.author: Sin
quotes.round_name: The Dark Side of the Tune

quotes.text: I didn't get time to write why this song dislodges emotion within me but I think about the women whose children I have been part of removing from their care over the years and the children who have lost their mother's. The emptiness that I know consumes them. Even the title 'doing the right thing', is a question that haunts me everytime I have to make a decision that will change the course of a child's/parents life forever.

I am the colleague who makes other colleagues put headphones on. (Literally, back when we were sharing a deskbank my colleague Jonathan used to put headphones on when I walked in the door). I certainly don't chew gum but I am known for typing way too loud (can't help it) and being super chatty.. It's why I laugh when people say they get more done in the office. Not with people like me about you won't 😈

Anyway nice tune

quotes.round_name: Ladies and Gentlemen We Are Floating in Space

quotes.text: I'm going for the brevity vote. Let's face it, at least half of the songs in this list will be a complete waste of four or five minutes of your life. Even if you don't like this it'll be over in less than a minute. Use the time saved to listen to your actual favourite song, make a nice cup of tea, or call a loved one. Then savour the warm fuzzy feeling that was enabled by this short song. And then give it three votes.
quotes.author: Matt
quotes.context: submitting 'Brave Sir Robin - From "Spamalot" Original Broadway Cast Recording'
quotes.song_title: Brave Sir Robin - From "Spamalot" Original Broadway Cast Recording

The night raised thousands for his kids - it was the best party I’ve been too. People swinging from pipes in the ceiling throwing money into buckets , these guys on stage. ervyone causing a riot in the best possible way. When I think of music and laughter I think of this

quotes.text: I feel like this is the kind of song that would play in a film where the protagonists are travelling on horseback over the wilderness for several weeks... Perhaps they find an injured wolf and nurse it back to health along the way... Then say an emotional goodbye when they finally reach their destination. Cut to the wolf, smoking a cigar and saluting sadly from a clifftop before walking off into the sunset

quotes.text: "Well it's into the guilt, and it's into the shame, and it's into the fuckin' fray." A tune for our league, indeed. Cave actually put out a live album with a version of this just a few weeks ago, and I know how much our Franks loves a live album - but it has to be this one because the live one doesn't have the verse about lynch mobs, death squads, babies being born without brains. Mr Franks, dis 1 u. <3

quotes.song_title: Papa Won't Leave You, Henry - 2010 Remaster

quotes.text: Considered one of his songs from Pi but they’re not on Spotify. Hey ho, what to say about this one though, or what’s not to say. Brooding, threatening, bittersweet and beautifully foreshadowing the absolute horror to come. Still remember the feeling of leaving the Prince Charles cinema when this came out. Now I’m going to curl up under the covers in the foetal position and cling everything I hold dear.

quotes.text: I was an intern at a music PR agency in my youth and I became obsessed with this band they were promoting. They let me go to see them and it was the tripiest sound I'd ever heard in real life. It didn't sound anything like the album, it was way better! I'd hoped they become famous one day and then, years later they had a gargantuan hit with a song I cannot stand. Funny how things turn out, ain't it?
quotes.author: Erica Silva

quotes.song_title: How The Leopard Got Its Spots

quotes.text:
Poor bastard. He'd see them soon enough.
This kind of west coast post-hardcore stuff leaves me really cold. The vocal harmonies are nice, drummer is a beast, Iron Maiden duelling solos were fun the first time round. Not sure this song knows what it wants to do. Four seagulls wearing eyeliner.
Budgiebabes is the designated downdoot sponge this week but it doesn't deserve to get fully buried. Sorry.

quotes.text: I have a playlist dedicated to other worlds, specifically for shamanic upper and lower world journeys. The upper world is a bit spacey, cold and lonely. I don’t go there often but the lower world is full of forests, animals and waterfalls (well that’s what my lower world looks like, yours might be different when you go there) anyway I have a playlist for that world - and this song is one of them
quotes.author: annamariawh
quotes.round_name: The Dark Side of the Tune

quotes.text:
I like how the verses in this love song are almost tetchy and grumpy: I find being in love irksome and I prefer to be on my own and I'm stubborn and set in my ways, but goddamnit now I can't be without you and I guess I can live with you and your idiosyncrasies, and you with mine.

That's love. Day in, day out, workaday love.

And then the chorus comes in, grand and sweeping and beautiful.
quotes.author: Sin

quotes.text:
When I was a kid, my dad played guitar a lot. Mostly old blues standards, but a handful of Talking Heads songs, sung with the same 40-a-day rasp and strummed chords.
The original version of this song always surprises me with its pared back synth sound, nothing like my dad's bluesy delivery, and not much like Talking Heads' usual style either.
But it is one of my favourite songs ever.
quotes.author: Sin

quotes.song_title: This Must Be the Place (Naive Melody) - 2005 Remaster

quotes.text: The title is based on a quote from Fear and Loathing in Las Vegas. "We can't stop here, this is bat country!" the protagonist is driving along high AF on drugs (Quaaludes, I think) and hallucinates a flock of bats. The whole song is based around this idea of being off your tits and not really knowing what is going on. Which feels appropriate for this round. Plus, it's a banger.
quotes.author: Kate Hitchcock

quotes.text: This IS a good song. Unfortunately however it makes me think of that super depressing film where Michael Caine plays an old man whose best friend is murdered by a gang of yoofs (they had this as the end credits). I believe Plan B was one of said yoofs in the film. Anyway, sorry, ruined the song for me. I don't want DNB to make me think about how badly society treats the elderly

quotes.text: Permit me to go Full Franks on this one, with apologies to whoever submitted it. Cook up a chunky hip-hop beat, sprinkle some random samples and a few piano chords on top. Add a female vocal in *completely the wrong fucking key* and presto, another Shadow banger. I just do not get the fuss about the guy, any of it. Not warm or cosy or zoney outy. Minus one spliff out of three.
quotes.author: Ben
quotes.round_name: Ladies and Gentlemen We Are Floating in Space

quotes.text:
Danny Boyle asked Tim Wheeler from Ash for a a tune specifically for the movie of the same name. 
The full soundtrack is basically a who's who of late 90s indie and rave - Oasis, REM, Beck, Sneaker Pimps, Underworld, The Prodigy - but this one stands out. 
Imagine writing a chorus like this and playing it in front of 10,000 people all singing it back to you. Pop punk genius.

quotes.text: It's just the coolest piece of music ever recorded. Who else would come up with that bassline - the last note of the phrase doesn't work at all with the chords it's under. Except that it does because it's leading to where the song ends up going, you just don't hear it until two minutes in when that big chord change hits for the first time. Still, a bit obvious for a vote.

quotes.song_title: Running Up That Hill (A Deal With God)

I love the bulging-eye rage look on his face in the YouTube vid of him doing this, the moment that made him a megastar. I mean, it's an annoying cockerel at 4:30am isn't it? Brief nailed, have your vote.

quotes.text:
Yeah, this is the stuff right here. I will never work out why they didn't invent grime MCs from Manchester until the 2010s, it sounds cool as fuck. 
Anyone tells you dubstep is dead, ram this down their throat.  Hostile, spiky, heavy, bassy, lovely. Soon as I've voted I'm checking out all three of these lads' output. Highlight of the round. Nice work Franco.

That first verse alone is a killer, and then the piano and waggly guitar in the second? Lovely. It could be 30 seconds shorter, maybe. The idea that he's supporting Oasis on this 90s revivalism mega-tour, rather than the other way around, is nuts.

quotes.text: This is the winner, surely? It's not my favourite Miles Davis stuff by any stretch but it is the original zone-out music. The guitarist fighting a losing battle trying to get himself in tune all the way through - absolute baller move. I like your moxie for putting a 20-minute epic in. Have a spliff - just one because this has some lively moments in it.

quotes.round_name: Ladies and Gentlemen We Are Floating in Space

quotes.text: From one of my favourite albums of all time, written as a lullaby for the eponymous Kaia , BT's newborn daughter who slept on his lap while he composed. He also invented several new stutter and glitch techniques for this album that have defined entire genres. And recorded a 110 piece orchestra. Lush. The entire album is a journey highly recommend x

quotes.text: Fun story, the first time I heard this, my Ukrainian friend told me it was in Russian. Turns out that was nonsense and it's a manipulated vocal sample (I think they were stoned when they made the claim 🤣). As the artist herself says, "music actually manages to be the language and communicates the emotions better than lyrics could ever be able to"

quotes.text: I didn't listen to Dark Side of the Moon until I was in my late teens, but I had this live double album on tape, and that was all the Floyd I could have asked for. This tour was in 1988 so Roger Waters had left and the days were numbered, but they sounded enormous. Listen out for the little snippet of Doctor Who, stay for the demented slide solo.

quotes.text:
Whoever submitted this, I love you. It's been floating around my head for weeks, unrelated to FML. Stunning piece of songwriting.

Most of those albums end on a kind of bum note, but this song is aight! We haven't had any Strokes yet, so I'm happy to be adding them to this crazy FML soup

quotes.text: It feels a bit like how I imagine life sounded to my housemates at uni when I was learning how to make music. I mean I think. I couldn't listen to much of it, obvs. If I'm reading your instructions right I'm voting based on this special tune while everyone else votes on yazoo, IE I should disregard yazoo. So yea sorry -1 just unlistenable

quotes.text: When my father passed away 7 years ago, I was unable to connect to any emotion. So I turned to A Northern Soul, for me the greatest album of that era and sang it full throttle at the top of my lungs until life's an ocean finally brought the grief out. Sorry I've turned that into a me thing but only to say the verve really do touch a nerve.
quotes.author: Bino

quotes.text: Man I'm really divided on this one. On the one hand, a lot of love for Frank and André. And I appreciate the oddness of the song overall. But the lyrics are weird and never seem to resolve into a coherent story/message. Unless it's that Frank's sensei whoops his ass for talking cod-philosophical drivel. In that case I'm here for it.
quotes.author: Sin

quotes.text:
I was introduced to kneecap in FML 1 with Rhinoket, a tune I quite liked for its novelty and funny lyrics, everything else I've heard since by them just makes me want to saw my ears off and this is no exception. Can't understand how they have become so popular. There, I feel better now.
Spared only by the car crash that is Tom waits
quotes.author: Bino

quotes.text: The collaboration is remembered as a pioneering crossover between rock's punk legacy and the burgeoning dance scene of the 1990s. Yeah as naturally as this just worked, getting John Lydon the face of punk to collab on a relatively unknown dance outfit was a bold move, yet they created one of the most iconic dance tracks of its tim.
quotes.author: Bino

quotes.text: This was my second choice, I wrote a long spiel for it. This show wouldn't have worked without the music - so often I found myself losing track of what the characters were up to because I was listening too closely. A single theme, four chords, that slowly evolves over four seasons? Shouldn't work but does. An absolute masterpiece.
quotes.author: Ben
quotes.context: on 'Succession (Main Title Theme) - Orchestral Intro Version'
quotes.song_title: Succession (Main Title Theme) - Orchestral Intro Version

quotes.text: A 'supergroup' of absolute mentalists. Their album this year was one of my highlights but this is from their first a few years back. I saw them at Glasto at 11am that year, and the singer barfed up basically a whole bottle of red wine on stage. He wiped his mouth, eyeballed the crowd, and said into the mic, "Brrrrrrrrrreakfast."
quotes.author: Ben
quotes.round_name: The Dark Side of the Tune

quotes.text: Dya know what annoyed me about this. It lulled me into a false sense of security for over two minutes . I’m thinking ‘ I like this im gonna give it a point’ then 2 mins and 30 seconds in I’m hit with it. I feel like something is knawing into my nervous system with sharp teeth whilst simultaneously giving me an electric shock …
quotes.author: annamariawh

quotes.text: Nothing like a tribal (Hopi) word sung in the deepest bass to make the waiting opponent shit themselves. Even if it just means ‘life out of balance’ - that mofo doesn’t know that, I’m gonna have a robe on, deep hood up and taking a slow stroll toward the ring looking like some Gothic Shaolin monk… giggling to myself inside.
quotes.author: Ghandi El-Chamaa

quotes.text: I hate listening to live recordings.... it's like oh yeh it's GREAT listening to people having an awesome time rocking out to bagpipes(?) and snake charmers(?) without me... Although I quite like the tune itself it's absolutely unhinged. Although also now I'm sad thinking about snake charming. Right that's it DOWNVOTE TIME😵

quotes.text: This was going to be my artist for one of the space rounds, saw these play at blue dot festival a few years ago (its a space themed festival) under the huge radar telescope, sun was out with a warm breeze, I was feeling fuzzy and hazy in the best way and then this tune just brought me to a complete standstill, mesmerized.
quotes.author: Bino

quotes.text: A really fun collaboration from 2011. At the time SBTRKT was a newcomer from Cambridge whose music focused on dubstep and garage. Little Dragon were a pop/ electronica Swedish band who were already pretty big having played with Gorillaz. Not sure how the two of them linked up but they made a really cool tune as a result!
quotes.author: Kate Hitchcock

quotes.text: Little Timmy is confused. It seems strange to hold granny’s open casket funeral on Halloween. Wait… who are those men in cloaks and why have they barred the door? Oh god, they’re drawing a weird circle on the floor in chalk. What is this music… Granny? Did anyone see Granny just move? GRANNY??! Arrrgggghhhhhhhh!!!!!

quotes.text: Yes this track is nearly 20 minutes long so I won't judge you for not listening to all of it (I will really, you're supposed to be zoning out, why are you in such a rush anyway?). The whole album is great, I could easily have chosen the other track instead, and is best listened to late at night when doing sweet FA.
quotes.author: Matt

quotes.text: The kinda woodwind that someone discovered they could play at an afters at 4 in the morning, but I'm really here for it. Cracking attitude to this one! Though I find myself wondering, does it go anywhere? Or is it alternating chapters of woodwind abuse and multi-bar power chord chanting? Ok yea thats the whole thing
quotes.author: basssbear

quotes.text: What was it about singing about #Surviving in the 80s? Gloria Gaynor, the Bee Gees, Elton John, Bon Jovi. Bunch of rich people hoovering up the marching powder, banging on about how making disco or power rock is like being stalked by a tiger or something. At least those others are bangers though, I don't love this.
quotes.author: Ben
quotes.round_name: It Was a Very Good Year

quotes.text: Listening to Pulp reminds me of the time I embarrassed myself in front of Jarvis Cocker at work by panicking and barging out in front of him and the Chair of our Board for literally no reason other than I saw two important people and had a dyspraxic freak out. I had to write an apology email. Also this song is meh

quotes.song_title: Do You Remember The First Time?

Through him a kind of knew this song already. I don't think I like it, but I love Blindboy and it feels extremely piss budgie to me, so have all the points!

quotes.text: You convinced your opponent of their demise before entering but some reflective lyrics meant that you doubted yourself - hence your face now looks like a collection of multicoloured balloons. An old friend in the crowd sees catches your attention, you cuddle furiously then decide to forfeit the fight in favour of a catch up in the stadium cafe. Your fight career is ruined but you went to the discotheque at the end of the night so it didn’t matter.

quotes.author: Bino

I'm afraid your conviction that this meets the script seals your fate.

quotes.text:
You wanted unlikely, so sit back, relax and enjoy a jazz saxophonist meld beautifully into gothic choral. 

When I first heard this it was on the radio in the car. I was so perplexed by the combo we all sat in silence as it played out on our drive, killing any potential road rage for that journey dead.
quotes.author: Ghandi El-Chamaa

quotes.text:
Have a nice creepy ASMR lullabye, everyone.

A collaboration with an unlikely band, it seems odd to me that there's a career in being Current 93.  He started out with Throbbing Gristle, Coil etc. in the very experimental days of industrial.  He now seems to do folk-ish things with bizarre spoken word.

quotes.song_title: All The Pretty Little Horses (Vocals - Nick Cave)

quotes.text: Lots of teary Radiohead songs but this isn't really one for me, even though it's an unbelievable tune. More...unsettling. After falling hard for the Bends and OKC, when Kid A dropped in 2000, it changed music for me all over again. Charles Cornell's breakdown of this one on YouTube is an eye-opener.

quotes.text:

quotes.text: I'm confused are you positing that non-french peoples are incapable of guiding blind people in chaotic situations ? What do they do instead? quotes.text:
Been confused about this one. 
First listen didn’t think of it much at all. Gave it a righteous downvote.
Second listen was a revelation. 
Third listen asked me a question. 
The answer was the inquisitive unthought revelation. 
OK.

One upvote for the mindfuck, friend.

quotes.text: I only recently discovered Ren, somehow popped up on one of my SM feeds and I was quite impressed. Haven't heard this before and I'm quite torn. Is it a story, no I'm not going to be pedantic, what it is is a masterpiece of lyricism and poetry, very creative. No complaints from me if this wins.
quotes.author: Bino

quotes.text: In a round full of strong contenders for a downvote I've gone with this one. Partly because I'm fed up of re-listening to them all to decide which is the worst and partly because it's first in the list so will probably do undeservedly well for that reason. But also because it's fucking annoying.

quotes.text: This is a beautiful little song, that I found when playing Hades, which IMO is one of the best games of all time with an incredible soundtrack. quotes.author: Kate Hitchcock

quotes.text: Really liked this one, slithers along perfectly, builds nicely, and the key change comes at the perfect moment. Not the full three because the snake himself would surely know the difference between poisonous and venomous. Body count: one tender-hearted woman who made a seriously poor decision.
quotes.author: Ben

quotes.text: Piss Bugies for me required an element of jazz saxophone, so  break-beat-punk, harsh noise, and cosmic jazz seemed to blend the chaos I was seeking. The invisible man is about the epidemic of mental health, grief and anxiety, let's face it we've all felt a bit piss bugies from time to time.

quotes.text:
The greatest misheard lyric of all time from our friend Andy when he was a lad. POPPADOM BRIDGE.

quotes.text: Suitably grand noise - horns blaring - suitably angry tune. You win on points after some back and forth - some say you turned the tide when you whispered in their ear “you get no cuddle” a strange lyric from the song which brought a great sadness to your opponent and the fight left them.

K'naan grew up in Mogadishu, but his family moved to New York (and then Toronto) to escape the civil war, after his three friends were shot at 12.

quotes.author: Sin

quotes.text: This is not a safe space, this is Effing Em Ell. But I think you'll do ok this week anyway, this is lovely. Hanumanamanabadman, we went to his birthplace in Hampi and had tea with the monks. This is super pretty but I am saving updoots. Something huge and elegant - a secretary bird.

quotes.text: Had a downvote for elsewhere but then changed my mind. This is a lovely tune but when I’m miserable hearing what a lovely day it’s gonna be just makes me want to stick my head in the oven, and it’s not even a gas oven. Plus I think this get a fair few upvotes, so here’s mine. Sorry

quotes.text: This track is from Gumi's album "Underwater", where all tracks have water/being underwater references. To me, the bass in this track feels like waves, at the same time as other elements feel like bubbles and currents. This a representation of water as a feeling, rather then words.
quotes.author: Gisele Neves

quotes.text: Love this, almost too groovy for me to zone out to, I kind of want to get up and shake my limbs to it. Some very aggressive nodding and foot tapping happening. I think it's too darn groovy for a point which is a shame. Definitely the best tune I haven't given a vote to all season.

quotes.text: This was such a fun period for UK dance. I'm not a house fan by any stretch but I do have a soft spot for this lad. Always a bit irked by her pronouncing 'static' with a hard t, and then rhyming it with a fully glottal-stopped 'automa'ic'. But, this is a jam, and a good choice.

quotes.text: First on the list that both fits the theme and also slaps! Though one might argue that if the deceased requests a song it automatically becomes appropriate, because it is appropriate to respect the wishes of the dead. so I've had to dock a point. Sorry I don't make the rules
quotes.author: basssbear

quotes.text: I went to a catholic secondary school as one of their 10% intake of non-faith students. It was hell. I appreciate that some might think this tune lovely, but for me, it is a horrendous sensory combination of old bad memories of school mass, with an offensively cheesy sax solo

quotes.text: This is one of my favourite Werid Al parodies, especially because it was accepted by the Amish community (I checked pre post) and also by Coolio (who initially got pissed, but then allowed the whole thing and joked about it). If you like it, I recommend watching the video :)

quotes.text: The final song on the original album ‘Coming from Reality’. Such a great tune and what a story this artist has had - was nice to have him as a secret for a while when ‘Searching for Sugarman’ documentary had just come out. That will get you into him if the music doesn’t.

quotes.text: Written and recorded in the wake of, well, all of it. 9/11, 7/7, de Menezes (..to Brazil). Setting these lyrics to a jazzy Big Band vibe somehow works a treat, and though the lyrics aren't happy reading, it ends on the most optimistic note. More prescient than ever.
quotes.author: Ben

quotes.text: There's only really one theme for the whole soundtrack, it's great though and turns up in chopped up oppressive guises.  This is perhaps its most cheerful, I couldn't be arsed with trawling through 15 versions of it to find the wistful one that is the best really.

quotes.text: I like your moxie for being one of two tunes this week that would never find itself on Top Of The Pops, along with Slayer. The Wiki page for this guy describes him as the father/originator/pioneer of acid house no fewer than 14 times, which is good enough for me.
